[5] New Zealand
Date: Thu 28 Mar 2019
Source: Stuff [abridged, edited]
https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/111604774/more-than-900-aucklanders-could-have-been-exposed-to-measles--public-health-service


More than 900 Aucklanders could have been exposed to measles, prompting the regional health service to contact those at risk individually.

It comes as Auckland Regional Public Health Service said there were now 10 confirmed cases across the region.

Four of the 6 new cases were linked to existing ones as they shared a household, but the other 2 were not linked.

They include a woman, in her 40s, who was infectious when she visited a number of supermarkets and a cafe, and a man in his 30s whose measles was confirmed in the past 2 days.

The service is following up with his family, work or social contacts, who may have been exposed to the virus. A further 62 non-immune people were in quarantine, ARPHS confirmed.

ARPHS's medical officer Dr William Rainger said health authorities had been "tracing all household, work, social or other contacts to check their immunity, discuss quarantine and monitor the appearance of any symptoms." These are standard public health procedures, he said.

Of the 10 cases, one was an 18-year-old student at the University of Auckland. When the 1st-year student was confirmed as having measles, ARPHS contacted about 600 people who attended lectures and tutorials with the person.

Meanwhile, Canterbury is facing an outbreak of measles, with 35 confirmed cases in the region. There have also been cases reported in Waikato, Bay of Plenty and Dunedin, according to ESR.

[Byline: Hannah Martin]

